ChatGPT said:

Nice building a trader simulator with real MOEX data is a great project. Below Ill give a practical, end-to-end plan: what MOEX offers, what to choose (historical vs real-time), concrete ISS endpoints and examples, pitfalls (rate limits / paging / timezones / licensing), and a ready-to-run Rust example that downloads CSV from MOEX and parses OHLCV into structs you can feed to your simulator.

Quick overview your options

  1. ISS REST (free / public) MOEXs Informational & Statistical Server (ISS) is the primary way to programmatically get market data (CSV / JSON / XML). It exposes current quotes, historical series, candles, trades and analytical products. Use this for most historical and delayed data needs. iss.moex.com

  2. Historical data archive / analytical products MOEX offers packaged analytical products and archive endpoints (e.g. "netflow2", other analytical products) that return CSV/JSON and are convenient for bulk historical downloading. Many docs contain examples and request parameters. MOEX+1

  3. Real-time low-latency feeds (paid) if you need tick-level realtime streaming for live simulation, MOEX provides low-latency market data feeds (FAST UDP / FIX / proprietary) that require subscription and setup (contact MOEX / use certified vendors). For a simulator that replays historical ticks you usually dont need this unless you need live market access. MOEX+1

  4. Community SDKs / wrappers there are wrappers and clients (Python, R, PHP, etc.) that demonstrate endpoint usage and can be used for reference while you implement Rust. x1o.r-universe.dev+1

Picking what to download

Decide by simulator fidelity:

  • EOD/backtest (daily OHLCV) use historical/analytical ISS endpoints or index historical pages.

  • Intraday (1m/5m bars) use the history/candles endpoints (ISS archives/candles) and pull per-day or per-range.

  • Tick-level (trades + orderbook) available via archive endpoints but large. Consider purchasing dedicated market data or using MOEX archive products; watch rate/paging limits.

Useful ISS endpoint patterns & examples

MOEX ISS is RESTful and supports .csv, .json, .xml. Example patterns (these are real URL patterns you can call directly):

  • Root / docs: https://iss.moex.com/iss/ the interactive documentation and endpoints list. iss.moex.com

  • Analytical product example (netflow2):
    http://iss.moex.com/iss/analyticalproducts/netflow2/securities/SBER.csv?from=2018-01-01&till=2019-09-01 returns CSV for SBER in that range. (analyticalproducts often limit rows per request; split ranges if necessary). FS MOEX

  • General historical / history endpoints: /iss/history/engines/{engine}/markets/{market}/securities/{SECID}.csv or /iss/engines/{engine}/markets/{market}/securities/{SECID}/candles.csv?... wrappers and client libs use these patterns to fetch candles and history. (See community wrappers for exact parameter lists.) x1o.r-universe.dev+1

Notes: many endpoints accept query params like from, till, iss.meta=off, iss.only=history or history.columns=TRADEDATE,OPEN,CLOSE,HIGH,LOW,VOLUME to reduce payload. Analytical product docs mention max ~1000 rows per request for some products you should chunk requests. FS MOEX

Licensing, delays and limits

  • Public endpoints often provide delayed data for guest requests; for full/real-time access you must subscribe. Guest mode may show 15-minute delay for some endpoints (apps show that behavior). For production or commercial usage check MOEXs data licensing and contact data@moex.com. AppAdvice+1

  • Some analytical endpoints limit rows (e.g. 1000 rows) per request implement chunked downloads or iterate by date windows. FS MOEX

Practical Rust example download CSV from ISS and parse OHLCV

Below is a simple async Rust program that:

  • downloads CSV from an ISS URL (you can change to any endpoint),

  • reads it with the csv crate,

  • deserializes to a struct with serde,

  • prints or stores rows.

Youll need these crates in Cargo.toml:

toml
[dependencies]
tokio = { version = "1", features = ["full"] }
reqwest = { version = "0.11", features = ["json", "gzip"] }
serde = { version = "1.0", features = ["derive"] }
csv = "1.1"
chrono = { version = "0.4", features = ["serde"] }

Code:

rust
use reqwest::Client;
use serde::Deserialize;
use chrono::NaiveDate;
use std::error::Error;

#[derive(Debug, Deserialize)]
struct Candle {
    // rename fields to match CSV columns you request.
    // Common MOEX column names: TRADEDATE, OPEN, HIGH, LOW, CLOSE, VOLUME
    #[serde(rename = "TRADEDATE")]
    trade_date: NaiveDate,
    #[serde(rename = "OPEN")]
    open: Option<f64>,
    #[serde(rename = "HIGH")]
    high: Option<f64>,
    #[serde(rename = "LOW")]
    low: Option<f64>,
    #[serde(rename = "CLOSE")]
    close: Option<f64>,
    #[serde(rename = "VOLUME")]
    volume: Option<f64>,
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn Error>> {
    // Example ISS CSV endpoint (change SECID and params as needed).
    let url = "http://iss.moex.com/iss/analyticalproducts/netflow2/securities/SBER.csv?from=2018-01-01&till=2019-09-01";

    let client = Client::new();
    let resp = client.get(url)
        .header("User-Agent", "rust-moex-sim/0.1")
        .send()
        .await?
        .error_for_status()?
        .text().await?;

    // Many MOEX CSVs include metadata rows or header blocks. 
    // If you get extra lines at the top, you might need to skip until header row.
    // The csv::ReaderBuilder below is permissive.
    let mut reader = csv::ReaderBuilder::new()
        .flexible(true)
        .from_reader(resp.as_bytes());

    let mut candles: Vec<Candle> = Vec::new();
    for result in reader.deserialize() {
        match result {
            Ok(c) => candles.push(c),
            Err(e) => {
                // Some rows may be meta rows  print and continue.
                eprintln!("CSV deserialize warning: {}", e);
            }
        }
    }

    println!("Downloaded {} rows", candles.len());
    for c in candles.iter().take(5) {
        println!("{:?}", c);
    }

    // TODO: save to local DB (Parquet, SQLite) or feed into your simulator.
    Ok(())
}

Implementation tips:

  • Many MOEX CSV responses include extra metadata and table separators. If you get parse errors, inspect the raw response and skip to the CSV header line (e.g., search for TRADEDATE then feed the substring into csv::Reader).

  • Chunk long ranges by date windows (e.g., from=YYYY-MM-DD&till=YYYY-MM-DD) because some endpoints limit rows/time range. FS MOEX

  • Use iss.meta=off and iss.only=history or history.columns=... to reduce metadata and limit columns when possible (reduces parsing pain and bandwidth). iss.moex.com

Storing & replaying suggestions

  • Store parsed data as Parquet (fast analytics) use polars crate or write Parquet via arrow crates.

  • For replay, store time-series in SQLite (with an index on timestamp) or local timeseries DB; iterate in time order to feed your simulator.

  • Keep timezone in mind: MOEX times are generally MSK (UTC+3). Normalize to UTC in your simulator. (App docs/guest mode mention delays/timezone behavior.) AppAdvice

If you need tick-level or live data

  • For live streaming or ultra-low latency youll need MOEXs FAST UDP / FIX feeds those are paid and need connectivity setup (and possibly a decoding library). Contact MOEX for commercial access or use a vendor that resells the feed. MOEX+1

Quick checklist to get started (concrete next steps)

  1. Decide simulation fidelity (daily / intraday / tick).

  2. For historical/intraday: pick ISS endpoints (analyticalproducts or /iss/history/candles), test one SECID in a browser to inspect CSV. FS MOEX+1

  3. Implement the Rust downloader (use the sample above). Handle date chunking & CSV meta rows.

  4. Store results in a local DB/Parquet and build a deterministic replay engine (advance time, feed candles/trades to strategy).

  5. If you need live data later, contact MOEX for feed subscription (FAST / FIX). MOEX

Step 3 Use it in Rust (super simple starter)

Here is a minimal Rust program that:

  2. Parses the columns you care about

  3. Prints the first few rows

Create a file named main.rs:

rust
use csv::ReaderBuilder;
use serde::Deserialize;

#[derive(Debug, Deserialize)]
struct Row {
    #[serde(rename = "TRADEDATE")]
    date: String,
    #[serde(rename = "OPEN")]
    open: Option<f64>,
    #[serde(rename = "HIGH")]
    high: Option<f64>,
    #[serde(rename = "LOW")]
    low: Option<f64>,
    #[serde(rename = "CLOSE")]
    close: Option<f64>,
    #[serde(rename = "VOLUME")]
    volume: Option<f64>,
}

fn main() {
    let path = "SBER_2024.csv"; // rename your downloaded file if needed

    let mut reader = ReaderBuilder::new()
        .flexible(true)
        .from_path(path)
        .expect("Cannot open file");

    for result in reader.deserialize() {
        if let Ok(row) = result {
            println!("{:?}", row);
        }
    }
}

  • Commas are used as decimal separators (European format: "57,30" instead of 57.30)

  • Volumes like "8,42M" need conversion (8.42 * 1_000_000)

  • The header is in Russian, so youll want to map/convert it

  • Quotes are used around numbers the CSV crate can still parse them

Convert volume suffixes

3. Fully working Rust example for your file

This script:

  • Reads your exact CSV format

  • Converts commas to dots

  • Converts "K" / "M" volumes

  • Converts Russian date

  • Stores data in a clean struct

  • Prints a few loaded rows

Its beginner-friendly.

Cargo.toml

toml
[dependencies]
csv = "1"
serde = { version = "1", features = ["derive"] }
chrono = "0.4"

main.rs

rust
use csv::ReaderBuilder;
use serde::Deserialize;
use chrono::NaiveDate;

#[derive(Debug, Deserialize)]
struct RawRow {
    #[serde(rename = "")]
    date: String,
    #[serde(rename = "")]
    close: String,
    #[serde(rename = ".")]
    open: String,
    #[serde(rename = ".")]
    high: String,
    #[serde(rename = ".")]
    low: String,
    #[serde(rename = "")]
    volume: String,
}

#[derive(Debug)]
struct Candle {
    date: NaiveDate,
    open: f64,
    high: f64,
    low: f64,
    close: f64,
    volume: f64,
}

fn parse_num(s: &str) -> f64 {
    s.replace(",", ".").replace("\"", "").parse().unwrap()
}

fn parse_volume(s: &str) -> f64 {
    let s = s.replace(",", ".").replace("\"", "");
    if s.ends_with("M") {
        let num = s.trim_end_matches("M").parse::<f64>().unwrap();
        num * 1_000_000.0
    } else if s.ends_with("K") {
        let num = s.trim_end_matches("K").parse::<f64>().unwrap();
        num * 1_000.0
    } else {
        s.parse::<f64>().unwrap()
    }
}

fn parse_date(d: &str) -> NaiveDate {
    NaiveDate::parse_from_str(d, "%d.%m.%Y").unwrap()
}

fn main() {
    let path = "your_data.csv";

    let mut reader = ReaderBuilder::new()
        .delimiter(b',')
        .flexible(true)
        .from_path(path)
        .expect("Cannot open file");

    let mut candles = Vec::new();

    for row in reader.deserialize::<RawRow>() {
        if let Ok(r) = row {
            let candle = Candle {
                date: parse_date(&r.date),
                open: parse_num(&r.open),
                high: parse_num(&r.high),
                low: parse_num(&r.low),
                close: parse_num(&r.close),
                volume: parse_volume(&r.volume),
            };
            candles.push(candle);
        }
    }

    // print first few rows
    for c in candles.iter().take(5) {
        println!("{:?}", c);
    }
}

Now you can turn your CSV into clean structured data.

Why Rust is a very good choice for this project

1. You are building something that benefits from predictability

Backtesting engines and simulators need:

  • strict control over types

  • reliable data parsing

  • zero mystery behavior

  • deterministic results

Rust gives you:

  • no silent type coercions

  • no NumPy/Pandas weirdness

  • no accidental None/null

  • no oops this was a float vs string issue during runtime

You get compile-time correctness instead of runtime surprises.

This is a real advantage for quantitative code.

2. You will naturally learn clean software architecture

Because Rust forces you to think about:

  • clear data structures

  • clean error handling

  • ownership of objects

  • data passing vs borrowing

  • modular design

These patterns transfer directly to other languages and make you a stronger developer overall.

Many Python quants eventually have to re-learn how to engineer software.
You will do it right from the start.

3. Rust avoids the biggest pain in analytics: silent performance bottlenecks

With Python, beginners often hit:

  • slow loops

  • memory bloat

  • GIL limits

  • heavy dependency hell

With Rust:

  • your loops are fast

  • your memory usage is explicit

  • you can process gigabytes of historical data easily

  • no GIL, no interpreter overhead

For any simulation with many candles/ticks, Rust is simply a better foundation.

4. You're building a foundation that scales

Right now you're parsing CSVs and running simple strategies.

In the future, you might want to add:

  • live data replay

  • order book simulation

  • multi-threaded strategy execution

  • agent-based modelling

  • JSON-RPC / WebSocket server

  • GPU/parallel backtester

Rust can handle all of that without forcing you to rewrite the entire backend later.

This means your early investment isnt wasted.

The only real downside (and it's temporary)

Rust makes you slow in the first months, because you fight the compiler until your brain adjusts.

Youre probably already experiencing:

  • "why is this borrow error showing up?"

  • "why cant I move this value?"

  • "why does lifetime cause this?"

Thats normal.

And here's the important part:

After about ~23 project-sized problems, Rust clicks,

and suddenly the compiler becomes a partner, not an enemy.

You go from:

Why is Rust so picky?

to:

This pickiness is preventing bugs I didnt even think about.

That shift is worth the early pain.

Youre learning much more than just the language

Youre learning:

  • type-driven design

  • clean architecture

  • correct error handling

  • modular code organization

  • performance reasoning

  • safe concurrency

  • deterministic program behavior

These are not Rust skills.
Theyre professional engineering skills.

Python makes it easy to skip learning them.
Rust makes it hard to ignore them.

Youre taking the better route long-term.

Should you regret not using Python?

No.
Python is great for fast prototyping, but:

  • you dont get strong foundations

  • you dont learn real engineering patterns

Youre choosing the harder path, but the one that builds a much deeper skillset.

If one day you decide to use Python too, youll use it with a Rust-engineer's mindset which will make you far more effective than someone who started in Python.

what are traits, implemenations, and how to use match?
ChatGPT said:

Lets break these three Rust concepts down in a way that fits your project and avoids unnecessary complexity.
Once you get these, Rust code will suddenly feel much less alien.

1. TRAITS capabilities / interfaces

A trait is a contract that says:

Any type that implements this trait must provide these functions.

Its like defining a role.
Not an object, not data a set of behaviors.

Example (fits your trading project):

rust
trait Strategy {
    fn decide(&mut self, snapshot: &WorldSnapshot) -> Action;
}

This means:

  • any strategy must have a decide() function

  • your simulator doesnt care which strategy it is

  • you can plug different strategies into the same simulator

This is identical to an interface in other languages.

2. IMPLEMENTATIONS making a type fulfill a trait

Traits define behavior.
Implementations attach behavior to a type.

Example:

rust
struct BuyTheDip {
    threshold: f64,
}

impl Strategy for BuyTheDip {
    fn decide(&mut self, snapshot: &WorldSnapshot) -> Action {
        if snapshot.candle.close < self.threshold {
            Action::Buy
        } else {
            Action::Hold
        }
    }
}

This means:

  • BuyTheDip is now a valid strategy

  • you can pass it anywhere a Strategy is expected

Your backtester:

rust
fn run<S: Strategy>(strategy: &mut S, data: &[WorldSnapshot]) {
    for day in data {
        let action = strategy.decide(day);
        // update portfolio...
    }
}

Rust chooses the right implementation automatically.

3. MATCH Rusts super-switch

match lets you pattern-match values.
This is one of Rusts most powerful tools.

Example: matching an enum (like your actions)

rust
match action {
    Action::Buy => { portfolio.buy(price); }
    Action::Sell => { portfolio.sell(price); }
    Action::Hold => { /* nothing */ }
}

Key points:

  • match must be exhaustive (cover all possibilities)

  • each branch handles a different variant

Matching numbers:

rust
match price {
    p if p < 100.0 => println!("cheap"),
    p if p < 150.0 => println!("medium"),
    _ => println!("expensive"),
}

Matching Option<T>

Very common in Rust:

rust
let maybe_value: Option<i32> = Some(5);

match maybe_value {
    Some(v) => println!("We have a value: {}", v),
    None => println!("No value"),
}

How these three concepts work together in your simulator

Trait: defines how strategies decide actions

rust
trait Strategy {
    fn decide(&mut self, data: &WorldSnapshot) -> Action;
}

Implementation: a specific trading strategy

rust
impl Strategy for BuyTheDip {
    fn decide(&mut self, data: &WorldSnapshot) -> Action {
        if data.candle.close < self.threshold {
            Action::Buy
        } else {
            Action::Hold
        }
    }
}

Match: apply the action to the portfolio

rust
match strategy.decide(&snapshot) {
    Action::Buy => portfolio.buy(snapshot.candle.close),
    Action::Sell => portfolio.sell(snapshot.candle.close),
    Action::Hold => {}
}

Everything fits together like gears.

Summary in 10 seconds

  • Trait = interface (defines required functions)

  • impl = connects a trait to a type (gives real behavior)

  • match = switch statement on steroids (handles enums, patterns, Optional values)

These three concepts are enough to build your entire backtester.

A struct is just data. Nothing more.

Candle (price data)

rust

    shares: f64,

A struct NEVER decides anything.
Its the state of your system.

Think: nouns.

2. ENUM different variants of the same thing

An enum is a type with multiple possible shapes.

Example in your project:

Action (what the strategy wants to do)

rust
enum Action {
    Buy,
    Sell,
    Hold,
}

Why this is useful:

  • you cant accidentally invent an invalid action

  • the simulator must handle all actions

  • perfect for logic flow with match

Think: categories or choices.

3. TRAIT behavior contract

A trait says:

Any type implementing me must provide these functions.

It does not contain data.
It only defines behavior / rules.

Example:

rust
trait Strategy {
    fn decide(&mut self, snapshot: &WorldSnapshot) -> Action;
}

This means:

  • a strategy must have a decide() method

  • the simulator can run ANY strategy

  • your code becomes modular and extensible

Think: abilities or roles.

4. IMPL attaching behavior to a struct

A struct is just data.
A trait defines behavior.
An impl connects them:

rust
struct BuyLowSellHigh {
    threshold: f64,
}

impl Strategy for BuyLowSellHigh {
    fn decide(&mut self, snapshot: &WorldSnapshot) -> Action {
        if snapshot.candle.close < self.threshold {
            Action::Buy

            Action::Sell
        }

Now BuyLowSellHigh becomes a valid strategy.

Think: giving a thing its abilities.

5. MATCH choose behavior based on an enum variant

match is your decision engine.

Example:

rust
match action {
    Action::Buy => portfolio.buy(price),
    Action::Sell => portfolio.sell(price),
    Action::Hold => {}, // do nothing
}

Rust forces you to handle all cases no forgotten branches.

Think: flow control.

You said:
 enum Action { Buy, Sell, Hold, } match Action { } but it says expected item, found keyword match
ChatGPT said:

Youre very close this error happens because match can only be used inside a function or method, not at the top level of a file.

Right now you have something like:

rust
enum Action {
    Buy,
    Sell,
    Hold,
}

match Action {    //  this is not allowed here
}

Rust expects only item declarations at the top level (structs, enums, traits, functions, impl blocks).
But match is an expression, so it must live inside a function.

Correct version

Wrap the match inside a function:

rust
enum Action {
    Buy,
    Sell,
    Hold,
}

fn main() {
    let action = Action::Buy;

    match action {
        Action::Buy  => println!("Buying..."),
        Action::Sell => println!("Selling..."),
        Action::Hold => println!("Holding..."),
    }
}

That compiles.

Why this rule exists

Outside functions, Rust allows only:

  • struct

  • enum

  • trait

  • impl

  • const

  • static

  • function declarations

Rust does not allow:

  • match

  • if

  • loops

  • calculations

because these are runtime logic, not type-level declarations.

Mental rule (easy to remember)

NOT allowed at top level:

  • match

  • if

  • for

  • while

  • let

  • expressions

Allowed at top level:

  • enum

  • struct

  • trait

  • impl

  • fn something() { ... }

Everything that does work must be inside a function.

ChatGPT said:

Heres the smallest possible Rust example that uses:

  1. struct

  2. enum

  3. trait

  4. impl

  5. match

Everything glued together in one tiny working program.

It simulates a strategy that looks at a price and chooses Buy/Sell/Hold.

Minimal working example using all 5 concepts

rust
// 1. STRUCT  holds data
struct Candle {
    close: f64,
}

// 2. ENUM  possible actions the strategy can choose
enum Action {
    Buy,
    Sell,
    Hold,
}

// 3. TRAIT  defines behavior that all strategies must implement
trait Strategy {
    fn decide(&self, candle: &Candle) -> Action;
}

// 4. IMPL  attach Strategy behavior to a concrete struct
struct BuyBelowThreshold {
    threshold: f64,
}

impl Strategy for BuyBelowThreshold {
    fn decide(&self, candle: &Candle) -> Action {
        if candle.close < self.threshold {
            Action::Buy
        } else {
            Action::Hold
        }
    }
}

// A function that uses match to handle actions
fn apply_action(action: Action) {
    // 5. MATCH  choose behavior based on enum variant
    match action {
        Action::Buy => println!(" Buying"),
        Action::Sell => println!(" Selling"),
        Action::Hold => println!(" Holding"),
    }
}

// Main program tying everything together
fn main() {
    let candle = Candle { close: 95.0 };

    // create a concrete strategy
    let strategy = BuyBelowThreshold { threshold: 100.0 };

    // strategy decides an action
    let action = strategy.decide(&candle);

    // simulator applies it
    apply_action(action);
}

What each part is doing (simple explanation)

1. struct

Holds data (the closing price).

2. enum

Defines possible strategy outputs.

3. trait

Defines what all strategies must be able to do (decide()).

4. impl

Gives a specific strategy its behavior.

5. match

Executes different code depending on the Action returned.

What youll see when running it:

 Buying

Because the closing price (95) is below the threshold (100).

what this does |?
ChatGPT said:

The | symbol in a Rust match is an OR-pattern.
It means this arm should match ANY of these patterns.

Think of it like:

If it matches pattern A OR pattern B, run this code.

Simple example

rust
match action {
    Action::Buy { .. } | Action::Sell => {
        println!("This is an active trading action");
    }
    Action::Hold => {
        println!("No action");
    }
}

Meaning:

  • If action is Buy, OR

  • If action is Sell,
    run the same block.

You cannot use partial patterns with |

Each part of the OR must be a full valid pattern:

Valid:

rust
Action::Buy{ .. } | Action::Sell

Invalid:

rust
Action::Buy | price

Because price alone is not a pattern.

With numbers

rust
match x {
    1 | 2 | 3 => println!("small number"),
    _ => println!("other number"),
}

So:

  • x = 1 matches

  • x = 2 matches

  • x = 3 matches

  • x = anything else second arm

With multiple enum variants

rust
enum Direction {
    Left,
    Right,
    Up,
    Down,
}

match dir {
    Direction::Left | Direction::Right => println!("horizontal"),
    Direction::Up | Direction::Down => println!("vertical"),
}

One more useful example

rust
match age {
    0..=12 => println!("child"),
    13..=19 => println!("teenager"),
    20..=30 => println!("young adult"),
    31..=50 | 51..=65 => println!("adult"), // OR used here
    _ => println!("senior"),
}

| in a match:

joins patterns
means OR
allows multiple patterns to share the same code
makes your matches cleaner and shorter

Youre reaching for something conceptually correct, but the syntax you wrote:

rust
stock: <Stock, f64>

does not exist in Rust.
But the idea behind it group two related pieces of data without making a whole new struct does exist.

Let's walk through the options.

Option 1: Tuple inside a struct

If you want StockInfo to hold both the stock and the price as a single combined unit, you can use a tuple:

rust
struct StockInfo {
    stock: (Stock, f64),
}

But this is almost never a good design, because:

  • You lose naming (.0 and .1 instead of stock and price)

  • It's less readable

  • It's less flexible later

So this works, but its not recommended.

Example usage:

rust
let info = StockInfo { stock: (Stock::Yandex, 31.5) };
println!("price = {}", info.stock.1);

It's correct Rust, just not ergonomic.

Option 2: Use a tuple without a struct at all

If your goal is minimalism:

rust
type StockInfo = (Stock, f64);

This is a type alias.

You can then write:

rust
let info: StockInfo = (Stock::Yandex, 31.5);

Also correct Rust.
But again, you lose expressiveness.

Option 3 (Recommended): Keep them separate fields inside a struct

This is the most idiomatic, clearest, and most scalable:

rust
struct StockInfo {
    stock: Stock,
    price: f64,
}

Why is this best?

  • You have field names

  • You can easily add more later (volume, open, high, etc.)

  • It's extremely readable

  • It's what real codebases would do

Example:

rust
let info = StockInfo { stock: Stock::Yandex, price: 31.5 };
println!("{:?} at price {}", info.stock, info.price);

Why Rust doesnt allow <Stock, f64>

The notation:

rust
<Stock, f64>

looks like C++ templates or a generic type, but Rust doesn't have standalone tuple syntax like that.

Rust uses:

  • (Stock, f64) for tuples

  • <T> for generic type parameters, but only in type declarations, not values

Example:

rust
struct Wrapper<T>(T);

If your intent is:

I want Stock and price to feel tightly connected, like one thing.

Then the correct idiomatic way is exactly:

rust
struct StockInfo {
    stock: Stock,
    price: f64,
}

This is unambiguously the right tool.

Rust encourages clear, explicit structs instead of squeezing multiple meanings into one field.

You said:
what is a type alias.?
ChatGPT said:

A type alias in Rust is simply a new name for an existing type.

It does not create a new type.
It just gives a different label to a type that already exists.

Basic example

rust
type Price = f64;

let x: Price = 31.5;  // x is still an f64 internally

Here, Price is just a nicer, more descriptive name for f64.

More useful example

Imagine you want to represent (stock, price) as one thing:

rust
type StockInfo = (Stock, f64);

Now you can write:

rust
let info: StockInfo = (Stock::Yandex, 31.5);

But internally this is exactly the same as:

rust
(Stock::Yandex, 31.5)

Nothing changes except readability.

Why use type aliases?

1. Better readability

Instead of:

rust
fn process(prices: Vec<(Stock, f64)>) { ... }

You can write:

rust
type StockInfo = (Stock, f64);

fn process(prices: Vec<StockInfo>) { ... }

Much clearer.

2. Easier refactoring

If you later decide that StockInfo should hold more data, you can update the alias in one place.

3. Shortening long types

Rust often produces long generic types:

rust
HashMap<String, Vec<(i64, f64)>>

You can alias it:

rust
type HistoryMap = HashMap<String, Vec<(i64, f64)>>;

let mut data: HistoryMap = HashMap::new();

Important: A type alias is not a new type

These two are still the same type:

rust
type Price = f64;
let a: Price = 5.0;
let b: f64 = a; // OK

Aliases do not protect you from mixing things.
If you want type safety, you need a real struct or a tuple struct:

rust
struct Price(f64); // now this is a NEW type

Summary

FeatureType AliasStruct / Enum
New name Yes Yes
New distinct type No Yes
Best for readability
Best for safety

  • how to wrap primitive types safely

You dont want a struct as the strategy itself you want a trait describing the behavior, and then multiple structs that implement that trait.

WHAT IS A STRATEGY, conceptually?

A strategy is not data. It is logic:

  • If price drops 5% buy

  • If moving average crosses sell

  • Always hold

  • Buy every 5 days

Logic = behavior
Behavior = trait

You may have many strategies, but they all must answer:

Given todays data and your portfolio, what action do you want to take?

Thats why a trait is perfect.

Step 1: Define a Strategy Trait

rust
trait Strategy {
    fn decide(&self, today: &StockInfo, portfolio: &Portfolio) -> Action;
}

This says:

Every strategy must have a decide function.

Step 2: Define Action

rust
enum Action {
    Buy(u32),
    Sell(u32),
    Hold,
}

Or more detailed if needed.

Step 3: Implement Specific Strategies

Example strategy: buy if price < 100.

rust
struct CheapBuyStrategy;

impl Strategy for CheapBuyStrategy {
    fn decide(&self, today: &StockInfo, _portfolio: &Portfolio) -> Action {
        if today.price < 100.0 {
            Action::Buy(10)
        } else {
            Action::Hold
        }
    }
}

Example strategy: sell everything if price > 200.

rust
struct TakeProfitStrategy;

impl Strategy for TakeProfitStrategy {
    fn decide(&self, today: &StockInfo, portfolio: &Portfolio) -> Action {
        if today.price > 200.0 {
            Action::Sell(portfolio.total_amount_of(today.stock))
        } else {
            Action::Hold
        }
    }
}

Step 4: Use Strategy as Parameter to Your Simulation

rust
fn simulate<S: Strategy>(
    history: &[StockInfo],
    portfolio: &mut Portfolio,
    strategy: &S
) {
    for day in history {
        let action = strategy.decide(day, portfolio);
        apply_action(portfolio, day, action);
    }
}

Now your simulation can run any strategy you pass into it.

This is exactly how Strategy Pattern works in Rust.

Step 5: Call your simulation

rust
let strategy = CheapBuyStrategy;
simulate(&history, &mut portfolio, &strategy);

Or swap the strategy:

rust
let strategy = TakeProfitStrategy;
simulate(&history, &mut portfolio, &strategy);

Why this is the right design

Strategy is behavior, not data use traits

Different strategies share the same interface trait

Simulation doesnt care which strategy generic type

You can easily plug in new strategies without changing code

This gives your project a clean, scalable architecture.

You said:
how to use match with enums in rust
ChatGPT said:

Lets make this super clear and practical.
Matching enums is one of the most important things in Rust, and once you understand it, youll use it everywhereespecially in your simulator.

What is match for?

A match lets you check which variant of an enum you have and extract data from it.

This is why enums are so powerful.

Example 1: Simple Enum

rust
enum Action {
    Buy,
    Sell,
    Hold,
}

fn main() {
    let action = Action::Buy;

    match action {
        Action::Buy  => println!("We buy!"),
        Action::Sell => println!("We sell!"),
        Action::Hold => println!("We wait."),
    }
}

This is the simplest form.

Example 2: Enum With Data Inside

Lets say your action contains values:

rust
enum Action {
    Buy(u32),   // how many units
    Sell(u32),
    Hold,
}

Then match looks like this:

rust
let action = Action::Buy(10);

match action {
    Action::Buy(amount) => {
        println!("Buy {} units", amount);
    }
    Action::Sell(amount) => {
        println!("Sell {} units", amount);
    }
    Action::Hold => {
        println!("Hold position");
    }
}

Inside the match, the variable amount gets the data from the enum.

Example 3: Destructuring Named Fields

If your enum carries data with names:

rust
enum Action {
    Buy { amount: u32, price: f64 },
    Sell { amount: u32 },
    Hold,
}

You extract data like this:

rust
match action {
    Action::Buy { amount, price } => {
        println!("Buy {} at price {}", amount, price);
    }
    Action::Sell { amount } => {
        println!("Sell {} units", amount);
    }
    Action::Hold => println!("Hold..."),
}

Notice: inside match, you dont write the field types again.

Example 4: Match Multiple Variants With |

| means or.

rust
match action {
    Action::Buy { .. } | Action::Sell { .. } => {
        println!("There was a trade!");
    }
    Action::Hold => println!("Nothing happened."),
}

{ .. } means ignore fields.

Example 5: Match With Conditions (guards)

You can add conditions:

rust
match action {
    Action::Buy { amount, price } if price < 100.0 => {
        println!("Cheap buy: {} units!", amount);
    }
    Action::Buy { .. } => {
        println!("Buy, but not cheap");
    }
    Action::Hold => println!("Hold"),
    Action::Sell { amount } if amount > 50 => {
        println!("Big sell: {}", amount);
    }
    Action::Sell { amount } => {
        println!("Small sell: {}", amount);
    }
}

This is super handy in strategies.

Example 6: Match Returning a Value (used a LOT)

match is an expression, so it returns values:

rust
let risk_score = match action {
    Action::Buy { amount, .. } => amount as f64 * 0.2,

ChatGPT said:

It sounds like you want two things at the same time:

  1. A list of scenarios you can loop through, like:
    run scenario 1 scenario 2 scenario N

  2. A way for Rust to force you to update the code whenever you add a new scenario.
    (So you don't forget to implement the new one.)

Rust is perfect for this.
And yes, there is a clean way to do it.

The Rust way: use an enum + exhaustive match

If you define your scenarios as an enum, Rust forces you to handle every variant in your match.
When you add a new scenario, the compiler will complain until you update the match.

Example

rust
#[derive(Debug)]
enum Scenario {
    MovingAverage,
    Breakout,
    MeanReversion,
}

fn run_scenario(s: Scenario) {
    match s {
        Scenario::MovingAverage => println!("Running MA strategy"),
        Scenario::Breakout => println!("Running breakout"),
        Scenario::MeanReversion => println!("Running mean reversion"),
        // If you add a new scenario later, the compiler will error here
    }
}

fn main() {
    let scenarios = vec![
        Scenario::MovingAverage,
        Scenario::Breakout,
        Scenario::MeanReversion,
    ];

    for s in scenarios {
        run_scenario(s);
    }
}

What this gives you

Run all scenarios in order

You collect them in a Vec<Scenario> and iterate.

Adding a new scenario forces code changes

If you add:

rust
Scenario::RSI,

Rust will throw an error:

go
error: non-exhaustive patterns: `RSI` not covered

This forces you to:

  • add it to the vector (if you want to run it)

  • add its match arm

Impossible to forget updating the system

This is why Rust is so good for simulations correctness is enforced.

Optional improvement: implement a trait

Instead of one giant match, each scenario can implement a trait:

rust
trait Strategy {
    fn run(&self);
}

enum Scenario {
    MovingAverage,
    Breakout,
    MeanReversion,
}

impl Scenario {
    fn run(&self) {
        match self {
            Scenario::MovingAverage => println!("MA"),
            Scenario::Breakout => println!("Breakout"),
            Scenario::MeanReversion => println!("Mean reversion"),
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let scenarios = vec![
        Scenario::MovingAverage,
        Scenario::Breakout,
        Scenario::MeanReversion,
    ];

    for sc in scenarios {
        sc.run();
    }
}

Still fully exhaustive, still compiler-enforced.

Even nicer: each scenario becomes its own struct

If each scenario needs different parameters, something like:

rust
trait Strategy {
    fn run(&self);
}

struct MovingAverageStrategy { period: u32 }
struct BreakoutStrategy;
struct MeanReversionStrategy { threshold: f64 }

impl Strategy for MovingAverageStrategy {
    fn run(&self) { println!("MA {}", self.period); }
}

impl Strategy for BreakoutStrategy {
    fn run(&self) { println!("Breakout"); }
}

impl Strategy for MeanReversionStrategy {
    fn run(&self) { println!("MR {}", self.threshold); }
}

Then you can store them in:

rust
let scenarios: Vec<Box<dyn Strategy>> = vec![
    Box::new(MovingAverageStrategy { period: 20 }),
    Box::new(BreakoutStrategy),
    Box::new(MeanReversionStrategy { threshold: 0.5 }),
];

for s in scenarios {
    s.run();
}

This is more advanced but very clean.

You said:
is there a way to access in print the name of the variable?
ChatGPT said:

Short answer:
No Rust cannot access the variable name at runtime.

And thats intentional.

Why

In Rust (and many compiled languages), variable names disappear after compilation.
They are only for humans, not for the running program.

Example:

rust
let x = 10;
println!("{}", x);

At runtime the compiled code has no idea that this value came from a variable called x.

What you can print

1. The name of an enum variant

This is possible and often what people really want.

Use {:?} or derive Display:

rust
#[derive(Debug)]
enum Scenario {
    MovingAverage,
    Breakout,
    MeanReversion,
}

fn main() {
    let s = Scenario::Breakout;
    println!("{:?}", s); // prints: Breakout
}

2. Labels you define yourself

If you want to print the name of something, attach a field:

rust
struct Stock {
    name: String,
    price: f64,
}

fn main() {
    let s = Stock {
        name: "AAPL".into(),
        price: 150.0,
    };

    println!("Stock: {}", s.name);
}

This is how systems normally do it.

3. Derive Display for pretty printing

Example:

rust
use std::fmt;

enum Scenario {
    MovingAverage,
    Breakout,
    MeanReversion,
}

impl fmt::Display for Scenario {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter) -> fmt::Result {
        match self {
            Scenario::MovingAverage => write!(f, "Moving Average"),
            Scenario::Breakout      => write!(f, "Breakout"),
            Scenario::MeanReversion => write!(f, "Mean Reversion"),
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let s = Scenario::Breakout;
    println!("{}", s);   // prints nicely
}

What about printing the name of the variable itself?

There is no built-in way, and it is considered bad style in Rust.

You can simulate it:

Hacky macro:

rust
macro_rules! print_var {
    ($x:ident) => {
        println!("{} = {:?}", stringify!($x), $x);
    };
}

fn main() {
    let my_price = 42;
    print_var!(my_price); 
    // prints: my_price = 42
}

This works because macros operate on the Rust source code before compilation.

You said:
what is "type"? i havent worked with it yet
ChatGPT said:

type in Rust is called a type alias.

It is not a new type.
It is just a shorter or clearer name for an existing type.

You can think of it as a nickname for a type.

1. Basic example

rust
type Price = f64;

let x: Price = 10.5;  // this is still an f64 under the hood

This does NOT create a new type.
Price is only another name for f64.

2. Why is this useful?

A) Makes code easier to read

rust
type Price = f64;
type Day = u32;

fn show(price: Price, day: Day) {
    println!("Day {} price {}", day, price);
}

Much clearer than:

rust
fn show(price: f64, day: u32) { ... }

B) Helps shorten long types

Rust types can get huge:

rust
HashMap<Company, Vec<StockInfo>>

You can alias it:

rust
type HistoryMap = HashMap<Company, Vec<StockInfo>>;

Then:

rust
let data: HistoryMap = HashMap::new();

Much easier to write everywhere.

C) Good for decoupling your code

If later you want to change:

rust
type Price = f64;

into

rust
struct Price(f64); // real new type with safety

you can do it easily because the rest of the code just uses Price.

3. Type aliases do NOT create new distinct types

Example:

rust
type Price = f64;

fn foo(x: Price) {}
fn bar(y: f64) {}

let a: Price = 50.0;
foo(a);
bar(a); // also OK!

Rust sees Price and f64 as the same type.

If you want a new type, use a tuple struct:

rust
struct Price(f64);

Now this is a new type, not interchangeable with f64.

4. Example from your project

Earlier, I suggested this:

rust
type History = Vec<StockInfo>;

This just means:

I want History to mean a vector of StockInfo.

It improves readability:

rust
let prices: History = vec![ ... ];

instead of:

rust
let prices: Vec<StockInfo> = vec![ ... ];

5. Real example you would use in a trading simulator

rust
type Price = f64;
type Day = u32;

#[derive(Debug)]
struct StockInfo {
    price: Price,
    day: Day,
}

This makes the intent clear:
price and day are not random numbers they represent something specific.

Summary

KeywordMeaning
typeJust a new name for an existing type (alias)
structCreates a new data structure
enumCreates a type with a fixed set of variants
implAdds methods to struct/enum

struct Candle {

Step 2: Custom parsing helpers

Because your numeric formats are non-standard.

rust
fn parse_f64_comma(s: &str) -> f64 {
    s.replace(',', ".").parse::<f64>().unwrap()
}

fn parse_volume(s: &str) -> f64 {
    if let Some(num) = s.strip_suffix("M") {
        parse_f64_comma(num) * 1_000_000.0
    } else if let Some(num) = s.strip_suffix("K") {
        parse_f64_comma(num) * 1_000.0
    } else {
        parse_f64_comma(s)
    }
}

fn parse_percent(s: &str) -> f64 {
    parse_f64_comma(s.trim_end_matches('%'))
}

Step 3: Parsing the CSV

rust
use std::error::Error;

fn load_history(path: &str) -> Result<Vec<Candle>, Box<dyn Error>> {
    let mut rdr = csv::ReaderBuilder::new()
        .has_headers(true)
        .from_path(path)?;

    let mut result = Vec::new();

    for record in rdr.records() {
        let row = record?;

        let candle = Candle {
            date: chrono::NaiveDate::parse_from_str(&row[0], "%d.%m.%Y")?,
            price: parse_f64_comma(&row[1]),
            open:  parse_f64_comma(&row[2]),
            high:  parse_f64_comma(&row[3]),
            low:   parse_f64_comma(&row[4]),
            volume: parse_volume(&row[5]),
            change_percent: parse_percent(&row[6]),
        };

        result.push(candle);
    }

    Ok(result)
}

Step 4: Use it

rust
fn main() {

    for c in &data {
        println!("{:?}", c);
    }
}

ChatGPT said:

Absolutely this is an important Rust concept, and once it clicks, the whole error-handling model becomes clear.

Lets break it down slowly and clearly.

1. What does Result<T, E> mean?

A Result is Rusts built-in way of expressing:

  • Success return value of type T

  • Failure return error of type E

rust
Result<f64, String>

means:

  • If OK I give you an f64

  • If ERR I give you a String describing the error

This is NOT the same as "return (f64, err)"Rust has no such convention because mixing success + error in the same shape is unsafe.

Why not return just an error?

Imagine this signature:

rust
fn parse_number(s: &str) -> f64;

What happens if parsing fails?
There is no f64 to return. You would need:

  • a panic (bad)

  • a magic number like 0.0 (dangerous)

  • a nullable type like Option (not enough info about why it failed)

Rust solves this cleanly with:

rust
fn parse_number(s: &str) -> Result<f64, ParseFloatError>;

Now the caller must handle failure.

2. What does map_err do?

map_err transforms the error part of a Result while leaving the OK part unchanged.

Heres what you wrote:

rust
fixed.parse::<f64>().map_err(|_| format!("Invalid number: '{}'", s))

Breakdown:

Step 1 parse result

fixed.parse::<f64>() returns:

  • Ok(f64)

  • or Err(ParseFloatError)

Step 2 convert error

map_err allows changing only the error:

  • Ok(x) stays Ok(x)

  • Err(e) becomes Err(custom_error)

The closure |_| format!("Invalid number: '{}'", s) means:

  • ignore the original error (that's _)

  • return your own nice message

Why |_| ?

Its shorthand for:

rust
|original_error| {
    format!("Invalid number: '{}'", s)
}

_ means I dont care about this input.

3. Why not return (f64, err)?

Because:

  1. You cant enforce "exactly one of them must be present"

  2. Code would always need useless checks

  3. Rusts pattern matching works beautifully with Result

  4. The compiler can help you avoid ignoring errors

This is exactly the kind of problem algebraic sum types (enum Result) solve.

4. Visual model (this helps a lot)

rust
Result<f64, String>
  Ok(f64)
  Err(String)

A tuple (f64, String) is:

scss
(f64, String)
always contains both.

Not the same idea.

5. When do I use map_err?

Whenever:

  • A function returns a Result<T, E>

  • You want to keep T untouched

  • But change E into something else

Example:

rust
let x: Result<f64, _> = "12,3".parse::<f64>()
    .map_err(|e| format!("Parsing failed: {}", e));

Summary

Result<T, E> is the Rust way of returning success or error

map_err transforms only errors

|_| means I ignore original error value

You dont return (f64, err) because its unsafe and ambiguous

If you'd like, I can also explain ?, which is the cleanest way to propagate errors in Rust.

What is Some(num)?

It is a pattern that matches a value of type Option<T>.

Option<T> is an enum:

rust
enum Option<T> {
    Some(T),
    None,
}

So any Option is either:

  • Some(value)

  • None

So what does Some(num) mean?

It is not a function call.
It is not a parameter list.

It is a pattern that says:

Match this only if the Option contains a value,
and bind that value to a new variable named num.

So if you write:

rust
if let Some(num) = s.strip_suffix("M") {

Then inside this block:

  • num is a new variable created by the pattern

  • It holds whatever was inside the Some(...)

Example

Imagine:

rust

Now:

rust

    println!("num = {}", num);
}

num becomes 123.

If x were None, the block would be skipped.

Case 2 string does NOT end with "M"

python

 None

Pattern:

scss
Some(num)

does not match skip this block.

These two arms return different types, so Rust cannot unify them.

fn parse_numbers(s: &str) -> Result<f64, String> {
    let s = s.trim_end_matches('%');
    let s = s.replace(',', ".");

    if let Some(num) = s.strip_suffix("M") {
        Ok(numbers_to_f64(num)? * 1_000_000.0)
    } else if let Some(num) = s.strip_suffix("K") {
        Ok(numbers_to_f64(num)? * 1_000.0)
    } else {
        numbers_to_f64(&s)
    }
}

  • If fails immediately return Err from parse_numbers

Best practice: validate before parsing

rust
fn numbers_to_f64(s: &str) -> Result<f64, String> {
    let trimmed = s.trim();

    if trimmed.is_empty() {
        return Err("Empty number field".into());
    }

    let replaced = trimmed.replace(',', ".");
    replaced.parse::<f64>()
        .map_err(|_| format!("Invalid number: '{}'", trimmed))
}

Example: draw price over time

rust
use plotters::prelude::*;
use chrono::NaiveDate;

fn draw_chart(prices: &[(NaiveDate, f64)]) -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let root = SVGBackend::new("prices.svg", (1200, 600)).into_drawing_area();
    root.fill(&WHITE)?;

    let (xmin, xmax) = (
        prices.first().unwrap().0,
        prices.last().unwrap().0,
    );

    let ymin = prices.iter().map(|(_,p)| p).cloned().fold(f64::INFINITY, f64::min);
    let ymax = prices.iter().map(|(_,p)| p).cloned().fold(f64::NEG_INFINITY, f64::max);

    let mut chart = ChartBuilder::on(&root)
        .caption("Prices Over Time", ("sans-serif", 30).into_font())
        .margin(30)
        .x_label_area_size(40)
        .y_label_area_size(60)
        .build_cartesian_2d(xmin..xmax, ymin..ymax)?;

    chart.configure_mesh().draw()?;

    chart
        .draw_series(
            LineSeries::new(
                prices.iter().map(|(d, p)| (*d, *p)),
                &RED,
            )
        )?
        .label("Price")
        .legend(|(x, y)| PathElement::new([(x, y), (x + 20, y)], &RED));

    chart.configure_series_labels().background_style(&WHITE.mix(0.8)).draw()?;

    Ok(())
}

3. Simple price-over-time chart (SVG output)

rust
use plotters::prelude::*;
use chrono::NaiveDate;

pub fn draw_price_chart(candles: &[Candle], output: &str)
    -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>>
{
    let root = SVGBackend::new(output, (1200, 600)).into_drawing_area();
    root.fill(&WHITE)?;

    // Extract X and Y ranges
    let (xmin, xmax) = 
        (candles.first().unwrap().date, candles.last().unwrap().date);

    let (ymin, ymax) = {
        let min = candles.iter().map(|c| c.price).fold(f64::INFINITY, f64::min);
        let max = candles.iter().map(|c| c.price).fold(f64::NEG_INFINITY, f64::max);
        (min, max)
    };

    let mut chart = ChartBuilder::on(&root)
        .caption("Price over time", ("sans-serif", 30))
        .margin(20)
        .x_label_area_size(40)
        .y_label_area_size(60)
        .build_cartesian_2d(xmin..xmax, ymin..ymax)?;

    chart.configure_mesh().draw()?;

    // Convert to (date, price) tuples
    let data: Vec<(NaiveDate, f64)> =
        candles.iter().map(|c| (c.date, c.price)).collect();

    chart
        .draw_series(LineSeries::new(data, &RED))?
        .label("Close Price")
        .legend(|(x, y)| PathElement::new([(x, y), (x + 20, y)], &RED));

    chart.configure_series_labels().draw()?;

    Ok(())
}

5. Add a Moving Average overlay (optional but very useful)

Add this helper function:

rust
fn moving_average(candles: &[Candle], window: usize) -> Vec<(NaiveDate, f64)> {
    let mut result = Vec::new();

    for i in 0..candles.len() {
        if i + 1 < window { continue; }

        let slice = &candles[i+1-window..=i];
        let avg = slice.iter().map(|c| c.price).sum::<f64>() / window as f64;

        result.push((candles[i].date, avg));
    }

    result
}

Update your chart:

    .label("MA20")
    .legend(|(x, y)| PathElement::new([(x, y), (x + 20, y)], &BLUE));
